  "opinion": "As a woman in Naples who drives for a living and has two children, I’ve seen firsthand how science can feel out of reach for many in our community. The gender gap in science isn’t just about fewer women in labs—it’s about the cultural messages that tell girls early on that math and physics aren’t for them. My father had a PhD, but my mother only finished lower secondary school, and that difference shaped my own view of what’s possible. When I was a kid, I’d watch my dad work late at the university, but I never imagined I’d be in a lab myself. Now, as a delivery driver, I see how many women are stuck in roles that don’t match their skills, like trying to fix a broken appliance or manage a family when they’re not in science fields. We need to address this gap by starting early, in schools, with role models who are women in science. It’s not about forcing girls into science—it’s about showing them that their curiosity matters, that their questions are valid. In Naples, where the Mediterranean sun shines bright but sometimes feels cold in the classrooms, we need to create spaces where every child, regardless of gender, feels seen. My own journey—learning to drive, balancing family, and staying curious—has taught me that science isn’t just for the elite; it’s for anyone who wants to understand the world around them. We should address the gender gap by building bridges, not walls, and by making sure that every child knows they belong in the scientific community.",
